In 2000, the city's age distribution was as follows: 18.9% under the age of 18, 8.1% from 18 to 24, 26.4% from 25 to 44, 26.7% from 45 to 64, and 19.8% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 43 years. For every 100 females, there were 95.1 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 92.8 males.

According to a 2007 estimate, the median income for a household in the city was $67,531, and the median income for a family was $92,057. Males had a median income of $52,287 versus $33,347 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $45,628. About 4.1% of families and 6.7% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 6.0% of those under age 18 and 4.9% of those age 65 or over.

According to ''[[Forbes]]'', Boca Raton has three of the ten most expensive [[gated community|gated communities]] in the U.S. The Royal Palm Yacht and Country Club holds the #1 spot, The Sanctuary takes #6, and Le Lac takes the #8 spot.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news| url=https://www.forbes.com/realestate/2004/11/19/cx_sc_1119home.html | work=Forbes | title=Most Expensive Gated Communities In America 2004}}&lt;/ref&gt;

As of 2000, English was the only language spoken at home by 79.9% of the population, while [[Spanish language|Spanish]] was spoken by 9.3%, [[French language|French]] by 1.5%, [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]] by 1.5%, [[Haitian Creole|French Creole]] by 1.3%, and [[Italian language|Italian]] by 1.1% of the population. Certain areas of outside of Boca Raton city limits, such as the [[Sandalfoot Cove, Florida|Sandalfoot Cove]] community, have significant populations of Brazilian and other Latino immigrants.

==Culture and attractions==
[[File:Aiken-house-boca.jpg|thumb|right|The Aiken House is listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].]]
[[File:Mizner Park Boca June 2010 Museum.jpg|thumb|right|[[Boca Raton Museum of Art]]]]
Old Floresta Historic District has several historic houses listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].

Boca Raton is home to the Wick Theatre &amp; Costume Museum.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://thewick.org/|title=The Wick Theatre and Costume Museum -|last=cwdev|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Festivals and events===
The [[Boca Raton Bowl]] is a [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) sanctioned [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] [[college football]] [[bowl game]]&lt;ref name=&quot;datetime&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.mlive.com/broncos/index.ssf/2014/05/dates_and_times_set_for_inaugu.html |title=Dates and times set for inaugural MAC football-affiliated Boca Raton Bowl, Bahamas Bowl |last=Drew |first=David |date=May 14, 2014 |publisher=mlive.com |access-date=May 14, 2014}}&lt;/ref&gt; that features the [[Mid-American Conference]] (MAC) facing off against an opponent from the [[American Athletic Conference]] (AAC) or [[Conference USA]] (C-USA) in alternating years. Each conference participates four times during the six-year agreement, which began with the 2014 season. The Bowl is held at the FAU Stadium.

St. Mark Greek Orthodox Church in Boca Raton hosts a popular Greek festival during the last weekend of January. An estimated 15,000 people attended the festival in 2018.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://www.thebocavoice.com/bocas-greek-festival-opens-thursday/|title=Boca's huge Greek Festival opens Thursday|last=Shatzman|first=Marci|date=January 21, 2019|website=Boca Voice|access-date=October 27, 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Additionally, the town hosts the &quot;[https://web.archive.org/web/20180122223549/https://www.festivaloftheartsboca.org/ Festival of the Arts BOCA]&quot; annually during the spring, and the Brazilian Beat Festival in the fall.

===Mizner Park===
[[Mizner Park]] is a [[lifestyle center (retail)|lifestyle center]] in downtown Boca Raton. The area contains several stores and fashion boutiques, restaurants, an iPic movie theater, and housing. The Center for the Arts at Mizner Park is on the development's north end, which includes the [[Boca Raton Museum of Art]] and the Count de Hoernele Amphitheater. Royal Palm Place is adjacent to Mizner Park, and it contains upscale shopping, restaurants, and apartments.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|title=Royal Palm Place in Boca Raton, FL|url=https://www.visitflorida.com/en-us/listing.a0t40000007qsRqAAI.html|access-date=2020-06-09|website=Visit Florida|language=en-US}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|last=Chokey|first=Aric|title=Nearly 300 apartments planned for Royal Palm Place in downtown Boca|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/palm-beach/boca-raton/fl-pn-boca-royal-palm-place-20170803-story.html|access-date=2020-06-09|website=sun-sentinel.com}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Town Center Mall===
[[Town Center at Boca Raton]] is an upscale [[shopping mall|super-regional shopping center]] in Boca Raton that is the largest enclosed and conventional shopping mall within Palm Beach County, and the third largest by square feet in [[South Florida metropolitan area|South Florida]], behind [[Sawgrass Mills]] and [[Aventura Mall]].

In 1999, the [[Simon Property Group]] bought Town Center at Boca Raton and began building a new wing on its southeastern side, and completed renovations in 2018.

Seritage Growth Properties plans to build a [[lifestyle center]] called The Collection at Boca Town Center which will provide shopping, dining, and entertainment.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|title=What Will Take Over the Sears Space at Town Center Mall in Boca Raton?|url=https://www.bocamag.com/boca-mall-sears/|last=Randy Schultz|date=2020-03-05|website=Boca Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200605023514/https://www.bocamag.com/boca-mall-sears/|archive-date=June 5, 2020|url-status=dead}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Crocker Partners will build a Restaurant Row near the mall.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|title=Restaurant Row gets a go|url=http://www.thebocavoice.com/restaurant-row-council-approval/|date=2020-01-14|website=Boca Voice|language=en-US|access-date=2020-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200605023603/http://www.thebocavoice.com/restaurant-row-council-approval/|archive-date=June 5, 2020|url-status=dead}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Beaches and parks===
[[File:Beach in Boca Raton Florida.jpg|thumb|Beach entrance in Boca Raton.]]
Boca Raton's eastern coast has two miles of beaches, notably Red Reef Park&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.ci.boca-raton.fl.us/rec/parks/redreef.shtm|title=Recreation Services Home|access-date=June 30, 2015}}&lt;/ref&gt; and South Inlet Park.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.co.palm-beach.fl.us/parks/locations/southinlet.htm#.USlWtTdrRqM|title=South Inlet Park|access-date=June 30, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512145234/http://www.co.palm-beach.fl.us/parks/locations/southinlet.htm#.USlWtTdrRqM|archive-date=May 12, 2015|url-status=dead}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Red Reef Park|url=http://sinkfloridasink.com/south-florida-dive-sites/south-florida-beach-dives/red-reef-park-boca-raton-snorkeling-beach-dive-site/|work=Sink, Florida, Sink!|access-date=February 28, 2013}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=South Inlet Park|url=http://sinkfloridasink.com/south-florida-dive-sites/south-florida-beach-dives/south-inlet-park-boca-raton-snorkeling-beach-dive-site/|work=Sink, Florida, Sink!|access-date=February 28, 2013}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Red Reef Park has the [[Gumbo Limbo Environmental Complex]], an environmental education center. Founded in 1984, Gumbo Limbo is a cooperative project of the City of Boca Raton, Greater Boca Raton Beach and Park District, Florida Atlantic University, and Friends of Gumbo Limbo.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Gumbo Limbo|url=http://www.gumbolimbo.org/about-us|access-date=May 11, 2014}}&lt;/ref&gt; In addition to the sea tanks, butterfly garden and boardwalk trail through the hammocks complete with an observation tower, Gumbo Limbo also houses a research facility run by FAU where students study coral reefs, sea turtles, sharks, sea grass and other marine-related subjects.

[[Sugar Sand Park]] is a municipal park in Boca Raton. It contains the Children's Science Explorium. Another park is the Burt Aaronson South County Regional Park in West Boca Raton. The park contains several amenities, including the Osprey Point Golf Course, a [[dog park]], the Sunset Cove Amphitheater, the Coconut Cove Waterpark, and the Daggerwing Nature Center. Spanish River Park is a family-friendly city park along the Intracoastal Waterway for picnicking, swimming &amp; bird-watching.

==Economy==
[[File:Office Depot Corporate Headquarters.jpg|thumb|right|Office Depot's corporate headquarters in Boca Raton, Florida.]]
[[Office Depot]], a supplier of office products and services, has its global headquarters on a 28-acre campus in the city.&lt;ref&gt;[http://mediarelations.officedepot.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=140162&amp;p=irol-newsarticle&amp;id=933195&amp;highlight= Office Depot Press Release.]&lt;/ref&gt; The [[GEO Group]], also has its headquarters in Boca Raton based out of One Park Place.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[http://www.thegeogroupinc.com/contact.asp Contact Us] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130063300/http://thegeogroupinc.com/contact.asp |date=November 30, 2010 }}.&quot; [[GEO Group]]. Retrieved on May 10, 2010.&lt;/ref&gt; Media company [[Friend Finder Networks]], hotel company [[Luxury Resorts]], consumer products company [[Jarden]] and e-retailer [[Vitacost]], and BMI Gaming are also based in Boca Raton. Hospitality establishments such as the Dell-owned Boca Raton Resort and Club, which serve the wealthy clientele of Boca Raton, contribute to the economy of the city.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|title=Boca Resorts, Inc.|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1020905/000095014404010621/g91728e10vq.htm|access-date=2020-08-07|website=www.sec.gov}}&lt;/ref&gt;

