===Higher education===
[[Florida Atlantic University]] (FAU), founded in 1961, held its first classes in Boca Raton in 1964. FAU is a member of the [[State University System of Florida]] and is the largest university in Boca Raton. It has over 29,000 students, 3,555 of which are residential students, and a Division I athletics program. In recognition of the rapid growth of Boca Raton's universities, in particular FAU, the city of Boca Raton has recently been referred to as a &quot;burgeoning college town.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;[http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2011-11-14/news/fl-boca-college-town-20111104_1_president-mary-jane-saunders-fau-college-town Boca Raton: A burgeoning college town prepares for change - Sun Sentinel]. Articles.sun-sentinel.com (December 27, 1992). Retrieved on 2013-08-16.&lt;/ref&gt;

[[Lynn University]] is a four-year co-educational institution renamed to honor the Lynn (Eugene &amp; Christine) family who continue to be benefactors of the university.

[[Palm Beach State College]] has its Boca Raton campus adjacent to Florida Atlantic University since 1983. When it was opened, it was named Palm Beach Junior College. In 1988 it changed its name to Palm Beach Community College, and in 2009, to Palm Beach State College.&lt;ref&gt;Palm Beach State College, Palm Beach State History, History - Timeline, {{cite web |url=http://www.palmbeachstate.edu/history/date-timeline.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-08-18 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909203012/http://www.palmbeachstate.edu/history/date-timeline.aspx |archive-date=September 9, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}, retrieved August 17, 2015.&lt;/ref&gt;

[[Digital Media Arts College]], founded in 2001, offers bachelor's and master's degrees in [[computer animation]] and graphic design.

[[Everglades University]] has its main campus in Boca Raton.

===Libraries===
The [[Boca Raton Public Library]] serves city of Boca Raton residents. A second municipal library building on Spanish River Boulevard west of I-95 opened in January 2008. The Glades Road Branch Library and the West Boca Branch Library of the [[Palm Beach County Library System]] serve Boca Raton residents who live outside the city limits.

County library card holders may use any of the sixteen branches in the Palm Beach County Library System and have access to many databases and downloadable e-books and audio books.

==Crime==
The City of Boca Raton is one of the safest cities in Palm Beach County, and with a crime rate 38% lower than the entire State of Florida.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|last=Comen|first=Samuel Stebbins and Evan|title=Safe cities: California, Texas are home to many of towns with lower violent crime rates|url=https://247wallst.com/special-report/2019/10/23/americas-safest-cities-3/|access-date=2020-06-09|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|title=Life in Boca Raton: 15 Reasons Every Day in Boca Raton Is the Best Day Ever - Movoto|url=https://www.movoto.com/guide/boca-raton-fl/life-in-boca-raton-15-reasons-every-day-in-boca-raton-is-the-best-day-ever/|access-date=2020-06-09|website=Movoto Real Estate|language=en}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Boca Raton has a connection to the [[American Mafia|Mafia]]. It is known as a popular hangout for many suspected Mafia members. According to a number of US Federal indictments, as of June 2004, the [[Gambino crime family|Gambino family]] continues to operate in Boca Raton. The television show ''[[The Sopranos]]'' featured the city in its plot (&quot;[[Boca (The Sopranos)|Boca]]&quot; and &quot;[[...To Save Us All From Satan's Power]]&quot;), and ''Mafia Wife'' author Lynda Milito resides in Boca Raton. [[Joey Merlino]], the reputed head of the Philadelphia crime family, also resides in northern Boca Raton.&lt;ref&gt;Brown, Julie K.. (September 29, 2012) [http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/09/29/3026287/joseph-merlino-the-mobster-next.html Joseph Merlino: The mobster next door - Florida]. MiamiHerald.com. Retrieved on 2013-08-16.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://bocaraton.com/index.aspx?pid=458 Boca Raton, Florida - Mafia Wife Interview with Lynda Milita | Boca Raton&lt;!-- Bot generated title --&gt;] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070819170338/http://www.bocaraton.com/index.aspx?pid=458 |date=August 19, 2007 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://cbs4.com/entertainment/local_story_044082354.html cbs4.com - Married To The Mob: Mafia Wife To Sue HBO&lt;!-- Bot generated title --&gt;] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927190839/http://cbs4.com/entertainment/local_story_044082354.html |date=September 27, 2007 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.harpercollins.com/authors/20964/Lynda_Milito/index.aspx|title=author-details|author=World Archipelago|access-date=June 30, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206090805/http://harpercollins.com/authors/20964/Lynda_Milito/index.aspx|archive-date=February 6, 2010|url-status=dead}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In 2007, several murders at the Town Center Mall gained national attention. In March, a 52-year-old woman was kidnapped and murdered. In December of the same year, a 47-year-old woman and her 7-year-old daughter were also kidnapped, and later found bound and shot in the head in the woman's SUV in the mall parking lot. This case was featured on ''[[America's Most Wanted]]'' and caused host [[John Walsh (television host)|John Walsh]] to say he believed a serial killer to be in the city. Though there is no forensic evidence to suggest the murders were committed by the same person, the similarities in the cases led police to believe they were related. To this day, the murders all remain unsolved.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/palm-beach/fl-boca-raton-town-center-murders-20150929-story.html|title=Killer in unsolved 2007 Boca slayings bought plastic ties, duct tape in Miami-Dade, officials say|last=Jacobson|first=Kate|work=Sun-Sentinel.com|access-date=2017-07-28|language=en-US}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/palm-beach/sfl-flpwanted0207pnfeb07-story.html|title=America's Most Wanted host: Serial killer at work in Boca|last=Fooksman|first=Leon|work=Sun-Sentinel.com|access-date=2017-07-28|language=en-US}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|url=http://cbs12.com/news/cbs12-investigates/have-the-murders-of-a-mother-and-daughter-shopping-at-a-boca-mall-gone-cold|title=Have the murders of a mother and daughter shopping at a Boca mall gone cold?|last=Angel|first=Greg|work=WPEC|access-date=2017-07-28|language=en-US}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/crime--law/four-years-answers-boca-town-center-murders/aroX1llFr2YR7hOG6xMvqK/|title=Four years, no answers in Boca's Town Center murders|work=palmbeachpost|access-date=2017-07-28}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The Pearl City neighborhood has been known as a [[drug trafficking]] hub in the past.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=d-0PAAAAIBAJ&amp;pg=4863,3300439&amp;dq=dixie-manor+crack+boca|title=Boca Raton News - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|access-date=2017-07-28}}&lt;/ref&gt; In recent years, the city, like most of the county (especially neighboring Delray Beach) has experienced a steady rise in [[heroin]] and [[opioid]] overdoses.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://thecoastalstar.com/profiles/blogs/heroin-linked-to-rising-drug-death-toll|title=Heroin linked to rising drug death toll|website=thecoastalstar.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-28}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/heroin-related-deaths-skyrocket-palm-beach-county-leads-state/rTDc1PqMwTLx25nN3rVzpN/|title=Heroin-related deaths skyrocket as Palm Beach County leads state|work=palmbeachpost|access-date=2017-07-28}}&lt;/ref&gt;

As of the end of 2019, the crime rate in Boca Raton was down 26% over the preceding 13 years.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://www.bocaratontribune.com/bocaratonnews/2019/11/boca-raton-police-chief-officially-retiring/|title=Boca Raton Police Chief Officially Retiring|website=www.bocaratontribune.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-29}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Transportation==
{{see also|Transportation in South Florida}}

===Air===
[[File:Boca Raton Airport Photo D Ramey Logan.jpg|thumb|right|Boca Raton Airport]]
*The [[Boca Raton Airport]] (BCT) is a [[general aviation]] airport immediately adjacent to [[Florida Atlantic University]] and [[Interstate 95 in Florida|Interstate 95]]. It has a control tower which is manned from 0700 to 2300. The Boca Raton Airport is publicly owned and governed by a seven-member Authority appointed by the City of Boca Raton and the [[Palm Beach County, Florida|Palm Beach County]] Commission.
*[[Fort Lauderdale-Hollywood International Airport]] (FLL) is approximately 23 miles to the south, in [[Dania Beach, Florida|Dania Beach]].
*[[Palm Beach International Airport]] (PBI) is approximately 25 miles to the north, near [[West Palm Beach, Florida|West Palm Beach]].
*[[Miami International Airport]] (MIA) is approximately 47 miles to the south, in [[Miami]].

===Highways===
*[[Florida State Road A1A|State Road A1A]] is a north-south road lying between the Intracoastal Waterway and the Atlantic Ocean.
*[[U.S. Route 1 in Florida|U.S. Highway 1]], locally known as &quot;Federal Highway&quot;, is a north-south highway passing through the city's downtown, commercial, and industrial districts in the eastern part of the city.
*[[U.S. Route 441 in Florida|U.S. Highway 441]] (also known as [[Florida State Road 7|State Road 7]]) is a north-south highway passing through commercial and residential districts west of the city limits.
*[[Interstate 95 in Florida|Interstate 95]] bisects the city from north to south with four interchanges serving Boca Raton.
*[[Florida's Turnpike]] is a north-south highway passing through unincorporated Boca Raton, forming part of the city limits in the north, with one interchange at Glades Road.
*[[Glades Road]] is an east-west road between US 441 and US 1.
* Other major east-west roads include Palmetto Park Road and [[Yamato Road]].
* Other major north-south roads include [[Military Trail (Florida)|Military Trail]] and [[Florida State Road 845|Jog Road / Powerline Road]] (Changes name on [[Glades Road]]).

===Rail===
[[File:Boca Raton Tri-Rail Station.jpg|thumb|right|Boca Raton Tri-Rail Station]]
*The [[Tri-Rail]] commuter rail system serves the city with its [[Boca Raton (Tri-Rail station)|Boca Raton station]] on the south side of Yamato Road just west of [[Interstate 95 in Florida|I-95]].
*Freight service operated by [[CSX Transportation]] and [[Florida East Coast Railway]] also serve the city.
*[[Brightline]] plans to open [[Boca Raton station (Brightline)|a station]] adjacent to the Boca Raton Library to be connected via bridge to Mizner Park in October 2020. It will provide service to [[MiamiCentral|Miami]], [[Fort Lauderdale]], [[West Palm Beach station (Brightline)|West Palm Beach]], [[Aventura, Florida|Aventura]] and [[Orlando International Airport Intermodal Terminal|Orlando]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |last=Baitinger |first=Brooke |title=Brightline station coming to Boca Raton by 2021 |date=December 11, 2019 |newspaper=South Florida Sun Sentinel |location=Boca Raton, Florida |url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/palm-beach/boca-raton/fl-ne-boca-brightline-game-changer-20191211-ciftkqv72rdffc63suhpjkt4te-story.html |access-date=December 29, 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt; With talks to connect to [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]] and [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]] in the near future.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/orlando/news/2019/12/27/virgin-trains-tampa-to-orlando-right-of-way.html|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2020-05-29}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|title=Brightline/Virgin Trains gets approval to raise funds for Orlando extension|url=https://www.jacksonville.com/news/20190409/brightlinevirgin-trains-gets-approval-to-raise-funds-for-orlando-extension/1|last=Tolliver|first=Laura Jazmin|website=The Florida Times-Union|language=en|access-date=2020-05-29}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Bus===
* [[PalmTran]] provides local bus service in the area.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.pbcgov.com/palmtran/maps_schedules/|title=Palm Tran Maps and Schedules|access-date=June 30, 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150704022606/http://www.pbcgov.com/palmtran/maps_schedules/|archive-date=July 4, 2015|df=mdy-all}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Water===
Long before any settlers arrived, the original 1870 government survey of the area&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.glorecords.blm.gov/SurveySearch/ Bureau of Land Management, General Land Office Records] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110123042359/http://www.glorecords.blm.gov/SurveySearch/ |date=January 23, 2011 }} Florida, Townships 46–48, Range 43&lt;/ref&gt; showed that just west of and parallel to the [[Atlantic Ocean]]'s [[coastal dune]] was the &quot;Boca Ratones Lagoon&quot;, which extended south for {{convert|9|mi|km|spell=in}} measured from just north of the present location of Atlantic Avenue in [[Delray Beach, Florida|Delray Beach]]. Along the southern half of the lagoon were three wide areas each called a &quot;Lake&quot;, which are now named (north to south) Lake Rogers, Lake Wyman, and Lake Boca Raton. At the southeast end of the lagoon was a short protrusion toward the south which would become the Boca Raton Inlet after a sandbar at its mouth was removed.

[[File:Lake Boca.jpg|thumb|right|Lake Boca Raton]]
The lagoon and lakes were part of a half-mile (0.8&amp;nbsp;km) wide swamp, west of which was scrub land a mile (1.6&amp;nbsp;km) wide (part of the Atlantic coastal ridge) where the [[Florida East Coast Railway]] (1896) and [[Dixie Highway]] (1923) were built. To the west of the scrub was a half mile or wider swamp within which flowed north to south the &quot;Prong of Hillsborough River&quot;, which is now the El Rio Canal. It now forms the eastern border of [[Florida Atlantic University]] and the Old Floresta neighborhood. The prong entered the &quot;Hillsborough River&quot; at the present eastern end of the straight portion of the [[Hillsboro Canal]] (dredged 1911–14), which is the southern city limits. The river flowed southeast in several channels along the western edge of the present Deerfield Island County Park, formerly called Capone Island (named for [[Al Capone]] who owned it during the 1930s), which did not become an island until the Royal Palm Canal was dredged along its northern edge in 1961.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url= http://www.royalpalm.com/art/pdfs/10_03_04.pdf |title= The Mysterious &quot;Capone Island&quot;: Deerfield Island Park |access-date= March 16, 2008 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20061019173651/http://www.royalpalm.com/art/pdfs/10_03_04.pdf |archive-date= October 19, 2006 |url-status= dead }}&amp;nbsp;{{small|(597KB)}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url= http://www.bocahistory.org/pdf/span_river/SRP%20Winter%201986.pdf |title= Deerfield Island - Spanish River Papers |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080802025816/http://www.bocahistory.org/pdf/span_river/SRP%20Winter%201986.pdf |archive-date= August 2, 2008 |df= mdy-all }}&amp;nbsp;{{small|(2.47MB)}}&lt;/ref&gt; Flowing south from the lagoon to the river along the eastern edge of the 'island' was a &quot;Small boat Pass into Hillsboro' River&quot;, also called the Little Hillsboro. The river continued due south about {{convert|4+1/2|mi|km|spell=in}} just inland of the coastal dune until it emptied into the Atlantic Ocean at the &quot;Hillsborough Bar&quot;, now the [[Hillsboro Inlet]].

The lagoon was dredged in 1894–95 to form part of the Florida East Coast Canal with a minimum depth of {{convert|5|ft|m}} and a minimum width of {{convert|50|ft|m}}.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url= http://www.aicw.org/browardlegacy.pdf |title= A history of Florida's East Coast Canal: The Atlantic Intracoastal Waterway from Jacksonville to Miami |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080509185248/http://www.aicw.org/browardlegacy.pdf |archive-date= May 9, 2008 |df= mdy-all}}&amp;nbsp;{{small|(3.8 MB)}}&lt;/ref&gt; After 1895, the lagoon and canal were sometimes called the Spanish River. Between 1930 and 1935 the canal was improved to {{convert|8|x|100|ft|m|abbr=off}} by the federal government and renamed the [[Intracoastal Waterway]]. It was improved again between 1960 and 1965 to {{convert|10|x|125|ft|m|abbr=off}}.&lt;ref&gt;Aubrey Parkman, ''[http://www.usace.army.mil/publications/misc/nws83-10/toc.htm History of the waterways of the Atlantic coast of the United States] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080310153813/http://www.usace.army.mil/publications/misc/nws83-10/toc.htm|date=March 10, 2008}}'', National Waterways Study, 1983, p.87.&lt;/ref&gt; All three versions were subject to [[shoal]]ing which reduced their depths below the specified minimum. Forming part of the northern city limits is the C-15 canal, connecting the El Rio Canal to the Intracoastal Waterway.

